<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <%- include("../parts/head") %>
</head>

<body class="d-flex flex-column min-vh-100 bg-wyrd-default">

    <!-- Navbar -->
    <%- include("../parts/navbar") %>

        <!-- Content -->
        <div class="container min-vh-100 bg-light shadow-lg border-start border-end border-dark-subtle">
            <div class="container-content">
                <div class="row mb-3">
                    <div class="col">
                        <h3 class="lora-semibold">Cosmology</h3>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <hr>
                <div class="row my-3">
                    <div class="position-relative p-0">
                        <img class="img-fluid w-100 object-fit-cover" src="/img/banners/cosmology.png" />
                        <div class="position-absolute bottom-0 end-0 p-3 w-50">
                            <div class="bg-black p-3 bg-opacity-75 rounded shadow">
                                <span class="lora-medium fst-italic text-light">
                                    From Limbo came possibility.
                                    From possibility came order.
                                    From order came law.
                                    And from law came life.
                                </span>
                                <span></span>
                                <div class="lora-semibold text-light text-end mt-2">
                                    The Book of Creation
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <hr>
                <div class="row gap-3">
                    <div class="col-md">
                        <p>
                            Every culture tells a different story about how the world began, origins of existence, and
                            the forces that shape them. Across kingdoms, temples, and forgotten ruins, echoes of an
                            older truth remain. Though myths and faiths differ, most share a common understanding of the
                            cosmos as a far greater reality, bounded by ancient powers and surrounded by realms beyond
                            mortal comprehension.

                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-semibold">Limbo</h6>
                        <p>
                            Limbo was the primordial void that existed before all things.
                            It was an endless expanse of unformed possibility, where existence and oblivion flowed
                            together without distinction. Nothing endured; all was swallowed by an eternal tide of
                            entropy that erased all shape, memory, and meaning.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            To mortals, Limbo is a dangerous place.
                            Every moment spent in Limbo erodes the foundations of existence.
                            The body begins to lose its cohesion as flesh, bone, and blood struggle to remain whole.
                            The mind unravels as thought, memory, and reason descend into madness.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Those who glimpse Limbo return fundamentally changed.
                            They may be haunted by false or missing memories, unexplainable illnesses, or visible
                            deformities, often accompanied by a lingering sense of dread.
                            Those who don't escape in time are consumed entirely, hastily dissolved into nothing.
                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-semibold">Elder Gods</h6>
                        <p>
                            The oldest myths speak of the Elder Gods, primordial beings who emerged within Limbo before
                            the first worlds took shape. They found no universe waiting to be ruled. Instead, they
                            faced an infinite void where every spark of creation dissolved into chaos. Through
                            incomprehensible feats of power and will they imposed structure upon the void to create
                            reality itself.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The Elder Gods divided existence into distinct planes, each governed by its most essential
                            nature. The elemental realms gave form to matter and energy. The celestial and infernal
                            realms embodied opposing spiritual ideals. Countless other planes arose between them, each
                            serving a purpose within the greater cosmic order.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Together the Planes of Existence a vast and interconnected tapestry separated by
                            boundaries that protected each realm from the others. Mortals know only a single world
                            within this greater whole, yet every soul, every spell, and every supernatural force draws
                            upon the delicate balance established by the Elder Gods. Though their works endure, the
                            chaos beyond creation has never ceased. Limbo still presses against the edges of reality,
                            and the barriers that hold it at bay require constant equilibrium to endure.
                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-semibold">Planes of Existence</h6>
                        <p>
                            Together the Planes of Existence a vast and interconnected tapestry separated by
                            boundaries that protected each realm from the others.
                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-medium small">Mortal Planes</h6>
                        <p>
                            The Mortal Planes are worlds governed by natural law. They are the birthplace of
                            humanity,
                            dwarves, giants, and others whose lives are shaped largely by their environment and
                            circumstances.
                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-medium small">Magical Planes</h6>
                        <p>
                            The Magical Planes overflow with magic and arcane essence in their purest forms. They
                            are
                            home to supernatural beings like elves, centaurs, and many magical beasts.
                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-medium small">Elemental Planes</h6>
                        <p>
                            The Elemental Planes embody the fundamental forces from which all physical creation is
                            built. Fire, water, earth, air, and other primal elements exist here in their purest
                            expressions and most potent forms.
                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-medium small">Astral Planes</h6>
                        <p>
                            The Astral Planes are realms of souls, dreams, memory, and thought. They serve as the
                            philosophical and metaphysical mediums through which consciousness, prophecy, and
                            inspiration flow.
                        </p>
                        <h6 class="lora-medium small">Spiritual Planes</h6>
                        <p>
                            The Spiritual Planes exemplify the beliefs, ideals, and convictions that provide purpose
                            and
                            meaning. Each embodies a particular worldview, where kindred spirits bond over virtues
                            and
                            vices alike.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

</body>

</html>